# Issue 3: “One SPI surface across all persistence tiers” is an unattainable goal

Architecture §4 #9 claims:

> “Durability tiers: in-memory (dev/W0) → Postgres checkpoint (W2) → Temporal child workflow (W4) — same SPI surface across all tiers.”

But the constraints imposed by the three persistence tiers are fundamentally different:

|Dimension|W0 In-memory|W2 Postgres|W4 Temporal|
|---|---|---|---|
|`NodeFunction`|lambda + closure|must be byte-serializable|must be registered as named capability|
|`resumePayload`|in-process Object|must be JSONB-serializable|must be Temporal Payload|
|`Checkpointer`|JVM memory|transactional SQL|workflow state managed by Temporal|
|`Orchestrator`|synchronous recursion|async + recovery|lifecycle owned by Temporal runtime|

The architecture itself acknowledges this.

§4 #15 states:

> “before W4, NodeFunction MUST become named CapabilityRegistry entries resolved by name, not inline closures”

This means the SPI surface must change, otherwise W4 Temporal integration is impossible.

The shape of the `ExecutorDefinition` sealed interface differs across tiers:

- W0:
    
    ```
    GraphDefinition(    Map<String, NodeFunction>,    Map<String, String>,    String)
    ```
    
    → lambdas are values
    
- W4:
    
    ```
    GraphDefinition(    Map<String, String /* capabilityName */>,    ...)
    ```
    
    → lambdas become symbolic references
    

This is a type-signature-level change, not “the same SPI surface.”

Fundamentally, the architecture is making a promise it cannot keep.

Rather than claiming “same SPI surface,” the architecture should define a layered SPI:

- stable cross-tier core concepts (`Run`, `RunStatus`)
- execution-layer SPIs (`ExecutorDefinition`, `Checkpointer`) with tier-specific constraints

