# Summary

|#|Architectural Problem|Affected Waves|Root Cause|
|---|---|---|---|
|1|`SuspendSignal` as checked-exception composition primitive|W0→W4|continuation semantics conflict with exception semantics|
|2|Sequential-only parent-child composition|W2+|unary composition primitive cannot express N-ary workflows|
|3|“Same SPI surface across all tiers” is unattainable|W4|persistence tiers impose fundamentally different serialization constraints|
|4|`Orchestrator` SPI overloaded with responsibilities|W1+|five independent concerns coupled into one method|
|5|`RunStatus` state machine lacks formal transition rules|W1+|states defined, transitions undefined|
|6|Untyped payloads across the entire pipeline|W1→W4|raw `Object` blocks serialization/API/streaming evolution|
|7|Tenant propagation breaks across suspend/resume boundaries|W2|ThreadLocal and RunContext propagation models are inconsistent|
|8|SPI defines states but no lifecycle operations|W2|half-defined state machine|
|9|No transaction contract between `Checkpointer` and `RunRepository`|W2|atomicity boundary undefined|

Among these, Issues 1, 2, and 4 are foundational architectural problems.

They determine the shape of the entire system, and the later they are changed, the higher the migration cost becomes.

Issues 1 and 2 amplify each other:

> unary composition primitives + exception-based suspension

effectively lock the system’s expressive power into:

- sequential
- single-threaded
- nested execution

as the upper bound of the model.
